**`src/hooks.server.ts` — sequential auth + plan fetch**

```typescript
// Current: two sequential network round-trips per request
const user = await getUser(event);           // → Appwrite
event.locals.plan = user ? await getPlan(user.id) : 'free';  // → Appwrite again
```

These could run concurrently when the user is known, but `getPlan` is conditional on `getUser` returning a non-null user, so there's no true N+1 here — it's just unavoidably sequential. However, `getPlan` calls `createAdminClient()` which constructs a new `Client` + `Databases` instance on every invocation.

**`src/lib/server/plan.ts` — new client per plan lookup**

```typescript
export async function getPlan(userId: string): Promise<Plan> {
    const { databases } = createAdminClient();  // new Client() every time
    const doc = await databases.getDocument(DB_ID, PROFILES, userId);
```

`createAdminClient()` constructs a fresh Appwrite `Client` on every call. Fix: module-level singleton.

```typescript
// plan.ts — cache the admin client at module level
let _adminClient: ReturnType<typeof createAdminClient> | undefined;
function getAdminClient() {
    return (_adminClient ??= createAdminClient());
}

export async function getPlan(userId: string): Promise<Plan> {
    const { databases } = getAdminClient();
    // ...
}
```

---

**`src/lib/server/altcha.ts` — `getSecret()` reads env on every call**

```typescript
function getSecret(): string {
    const secret = env.ALTCHA_SECRET?.trim();  // called per verifySolution/createChallenge
```

Since env vars don't change at runtime, memoize:

```typescript
let _secret: string | undefined;
function getSecret(): string {
    if (_secret) return _secret;
    const secret = env.ALTCHA_SECRET?.trim();
    if (!secret) {
        if (!dev) throw new Error('ALTCHA_SECRET is not set');
        return (_secret = 'dev-insecure-altcha-secret-change-me');
    }
    return (_secret = secret);
}
```

**`src/lib/server/kv.ts` — already uses module-level singleton** — this is well done.

**`src/lib/server/search.ts` — `GROQ_MODEL` constant** — already memoized at module level. Good.

**`src/lib/server/ai.ts` — local `answerCache` LRU is insertion-order only**

The current eviction removes the *oldest-inserted* entry, not the *least recently used* one. Under a skewed query distribution, popular entries get evicted while stale ones linger. A simple fix using `Map`'s re-insertion to simulate LRU:

```typescript
// On cache hit, move to end (most-recently-used position)
export async function getCachedAnswer(query: string): Promise<AnswerResult | null> {
    const entry = answerCache.get(query);
    if (!entry) return null;
    if (entry.expiresAt <= Date.now()) { answerCache.delete(query); return null; }
    // Re-insert to mark as recently used
    answerCache.delete(query);
    answerCache.set(query, entry);
    return entry.result;
}
```

The same applies to `searchCache` in `search.ts`.

---

**`src/lib/server/altcha.ts` — `usedSignatures` grows unboundedly between calls**

```typescript
const usedSignatures = new Map<string, number>();
function pruneUsed(now: number): void {
    for (const [sig, expiresAt] of usedSignatures) {
        if (expiresAt <= now) usedSignatures.delete(sig);
    }
}
```

`pruneUsed` is only called inside `verifySolution`. If no challenges are verified for a long period, entries accumulate. On a serverless platform this is mitigated by instance recycling, but on a long-lived Node process (dev or self-hosted) this leaks. The `O(n)` scan on every verify also becomes expensive under load.

Fix: cap the map size or schedule periodic pruning.

```typescript
// After inserting, cap to prevent unbounded growth
usedSignatures.set(decoded.signature, expires);
if (usedSignatures.size > 10_000) {
    // Drop oldest (first inserted) entries
    for (const key of usedSignatures.keys()) {
        usedSignatures.delete(key);
        if (usedSignatures.size <= 8_000) break;
    }
}
```

**`src/lib/server/security.ts` — same pattern, same risk**

```typescript
const clients = new Map<string, Entry>();
function prune(now: number): void { /* only called from flagSuspicious */ }
```

`prune` is called only from `flagSuspicious`, not from `isVerified` or `challengeRequired`. A long-running instance that stops flagging new clients will never prune old ones. Add a call to `prune` in the read paths, or use the same cap pattern.

**`src/lib/server/search.ts` — `rateLimitBuckets` map is never pruned**

```typescript
const rateLimitBuckets = new Map<string, TokenBucketState>();
```

There's no eviction logic visible for this map. Every unique IP that hits the search endpoint adds a permanent entry. Fix: evict entries whose `updatedAt` is older than `RATE_LIMIT_STATE_TTL_MS` during rate-limit checks.

